%\centerline{{\it Abstract}}
\begin{abstract}
\noindent
{\small %\em 
An enhancement of vortex-motion damping in thin Pb/In superconducting
films is obtained through coupling to an adjacent two-dimensional
electron gas formed in a modulation-doped GaAs/AlGaAs heterostructure.
This effect is observed by monitoring the power dissipation 
at the superconductor in the vortex state while increasing the
density of the electron gas using a gate voltage. Quantitative agreement
is found with calculations based on a viscous model of vortex damping
which considers generation of eddy currents in the electron gas by
moving flux lines. In the regime of filamentary and channel vortex
flow, eddy-current damping leads to striking dissipation breakdown
due to stopping of entire vortex channels.}
\end{abstract}

